 enabled="false" /><nav_data><outline><links><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6dP3Q4rvFns" displaytext="Slide 1" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6KngmsYFZ1q" displaytext="Slide 2" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.62ypsI2AALP" displaytext="Slide 3" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6eXgv5DZ15o" displaytext="It takes too long - The course is the equivalent of the 30 hour course you could have taken in a classroom on at least four (4) Saturdays instead of whatever you would have done on a Saturday.   Noticed what I just said? “equivalent” of the 30 hours course! You know what “equivalent” means ? It means also 30 hours!  Oh yes, and there is the DMV!  The DMV requires the course to be an “equivalent” of the 30 hours! That’s not my idea.  So now we have a choice: I can read fast as many of you can do and then you can sit and stare at the screen whilst a timer is running.  We thought it to be a better Idea to do it slowly. The key to learning is comprehension, not speed!" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6qSkZmvpu7Q" displaytext="Slide 5" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.5mzczeQu1kM" displaytext="I don’t want to know all this - You may want to complain about all these things you are being told to learn. You don’t want to hear them. You want to get on with the course and finish it! You want to get your license! Correct?   Hold it.   There are DMV requirements. You will NOT get a permit unless you listen to everything “I am required to tell you”. There are rules to follow.   Like it or not, the rules are here to stay." expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6ngTVsTR9xh" displaytext="It’s boring - the course material may be boring to you. So be it. You want to get a driver’s license, correct? It does not matter where you take a Driver’s Ed class. The material is the same. The rules are the same.   We tried to make it as convenient as possible for you. The key to survival in traffic is to learn something first.   Driving is a complex issue:   physical, mental and financial." expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.5ZeMcLraSCs" displaytext="Slide 8" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.5nqEi9vVLxS" displaytext="The Lady has an accent – Come on now. America is a mixture of cultures. Next time you are listening to people, check it out. If the people are of Mexican or South American descent, they will have an accent. If they are Irish – they will have an accent.  Italian – accent. German – ditto. If they are Chinese, Japanese, Korean etc. – same here.   Here is a point to ponder:   I declare that I speak English and YOU have an accent!" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6HQNzmMApYQ" displaytext="Rule for quizzes/test:  After every lesson you are required to take a test.   If you PASS the test: you will automatically advance to the next lesson.     If you FAIL the test: you will need to repeat the entire lesson again. No exceptions.     It’s a rule. Just like driving on the right side of the road." expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6rTsxX5LPpL" displaytext="One more thing - Oh yes, here is one more thing to remember. Your progress is being monitored and recorded on a data base.    So, please, don’t embarrass yourself.      Do not call your driving school and complain that  “…I have finished Lesson 7 and the system put me back to lesson 4…”.   		It only takes a couple of keystrokes for your driving 			school to find out exactly when you have started a 			lesson, finished a lesson, and how much time you have 		spent on a given lesson/chapter.   		That applies to the quizzes/tests as well.   		It is also being recorded if you have passed a test or 			failed a test." expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6ml4BJwCgR2" displaytext="I am glad this is all out of the way.   So, let’s start!" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.5upy9za9NNN" displaytext="Slide 13" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6ZlrJNNZWCK" displaytext="Privilege" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.64Av75vTLop" displaytext="Slide 15" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6LXw3QIeX2p" displaytext="Slide 16" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6lZAs4QBbfL" displaytext="Slide 17" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.5jhftzAQRDO" displaytext="Slide 18" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.5ZGBrFjakNA" displaytext="Slide 19" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6RxPG5mLzzn" displaytext="Under18Requirements" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6lFZYQEwYQa" displaytext="Slide 21" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.5ZFWVIMe3QZ" displaytext="Slide 22" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.5fLwfdSdHpI" displaytext="Slide 23" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6ONugcHAHJi" displaytext="Slide 24" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6kqd57E2Qe2" displaytext="Slide 25" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6BUff2uAq6o" displaytext="Slide 26" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6ju66UcLkWU" displaytext="Co-operative Driving" expand="false" type="slide" /><slidelink slideid="5wJ6qVSs2jN.6bZ6cctsCTk" displaytext="Slide 28" expand="false" type="slide" /></links></outline></nav_data><resource_data description="" /><transcript_data /><glossary_data /></bwFrame>